A Decision-Language Model (DLM) for Dynamic Restless
Multi-Armed Bandit Tasks in Public Health

Aparna Taneja 2 Dheeraj Nagaraj 2 &Milind Tambe 1,2

Abstract

Efforts to reduce maternal mortality rate, a key UN Sustainable Development target (SDG Target 3.1), rely largely on preventative care programs to spread critical health information to high-risk populations. These programs face two important challenges: efficiently allocating limited health resources to large beneficiary populations, and adapting to evolving policy priorities. While prior works in restless multi-armed bandit (RMAB) demonstrated success in public health allocation tasks, they lack flexibility to adapt to evolving policy priorities. Concurrently, Large Language Models (LLMs) have emerged as adept, automated planners in various domains, including robotic control and navigation. In this paper, we propose DLM: a Decision Language Model for RMABs. To enable dynamic fine-tuning of RMAB policies for challenging public health settings using human-language commands, we propose using LLMs as automated planners to (1) interpret human policy preference prompts, (2) propose code reward functions for a multi-agent RL environment for RMABs, and (3) iterate on the generated reward using feedback from RMAB simulations to effectively adapt policy outcomes. In collaboration with ARMMAN, an India-based public health organization promoting preventative care for pregnant mothers, we conduct a simulation study , showing DLM can dynamically shape policy outcomes using only human language commands as input.

1 Introduction

Maternal and child health is a critical public health priority worldwide. Recent estimates indicate that the global maternal mortality ratio is more than double the UN Sustainable Development Goal target (SDG Target 3.1) of below 70 deaths per 100K live births UnitedÂ Nations and Development ( 2015 ) . Maternal mortality (MM) is of particular concern for low and middle-income countries, which account for 99% of global maternal deaths Kurjak et al. ( 2023 ) . Further, a large portion of MMs stem from preventable causes Organization and others ( 2015 ) ; as such, programs promoting preventative care awareness, for example through mobile health platforms, have shown to considerably improve access to essential care information Choudhury et al. ( 2021 ) .

However, two key problems remain for these preventative care programs, often operated by non-profits supporting low-resource communities HelpMum ( 2023 ); ARMMAN ( 2019 ) . First, these programs typically operate with insufficient financial and human resources, highlighting the need for effective resource allocation strategies to maximize health outcomes Kruk et al. ( 2018 ); Baltussen and Niessen ( 2006 ) . Second, these programs must frequently adapt to changing population needs and intervention priorities Organization and others ( 2015 ) . Adaptability is especially important for prioritizing care for known subpopulations with higher risk GrÃ¤ler et al. ( 2022 ) , and for adjusting strategies using community or expert-driven insights Deardorff et al. ( 2018 ) .

Restless multi-armed bandits (RMAB) have been shown to be successful in modelling resource allocation in public health Nishtala et al. ( 2023 ); Wang et al. ( 2023 ) . In the classical RMAB formulation, a central planner chooses arms to allocate resources and observes state-dependent reward from arms. Despite the strength of RMABs in planning resource allocation, a significant challenge persists in developing models capable of adapting to changing policy objectives. For example, public health experts may wish to use RMAB models to direct resources towards specific underprivileged subpopulations. However, existing works in RMABs focus on fixed policy objectives and require significant human tuning and re-training to meet new desired health outcome.

Recently, large language models (LLMs) have emerged as powerful planners in a wide variety of tasks including navigation Shah et al. ( 2023 ) , spatio-temporal reasoning Vemprala et al. ( 2023 ) , and interactive decision-making Li et al. ( 2022 ) . Recent works have also shown that LLMs can be used directly as code generators to propose reward functions for reinforcement learning (RL) to complete complex robotic manipulation tasks Ma et al. ( 2024 ) . However, the ability of LLMs as planners for resource allocation in real-world public health settings remains unstudied. This planning ability is especially useful for non-profits that have evolving priorities but do not have the capacity to frequently retrain models.

We propose a Decision Language Model for RMABs, combining strengths of LLMs in semantic comprehension, code generation, and in-context learning, with the efficiency of RMAB modeling in resource allocation for public health. To enable rapid policy adjustment using human language commands, we propose: 1) using LLMs to disambiguate human-expressed policy preferences, 2) using LLMs to directly propose reward functions as code to reach desired RMAB objectives, and 3) a mechanism for iteratively refining LLM-generated reward functions without any ground truth feedback. Using simulation results of LLM-proposed reward functions, we continually improve the alignment of reward functions towards specified goals.

We partner with the India-based non-profit ARMMAN, a public health organization that spreads preventative care awareness to pregnant mothers through an automated phone-based messaging system. To increase retention, ARMMAN employs health workers to provide service calls to beneficiaries. Due to limited support staff, this assignment is similar to a limited resource allocation problem. Prior works have used RMABs to model the user retention problem in the ARMMAN setting Killian et al. ( 2023 ); Wang et al. ( 2023 ) , but they fail to address evolving priorities of ARMMAN.

In summary, our key contributions are as follows:

  • â€¢

    To the best of our knowledge, we are the first to propose using LLMs to adapt to changing resource allocation objectives in public health through reward design.

  • â€¢

    We introduce a reward proposal loop that enhances LLM-generated reward functions using feedback from restless multi-armed bandit (RMAB) simulations, enabling LLMs to iteratively refine reward design to achieve specific, human-specified policy outcomes.

  • â€¢

    To assess the feasibility of deploying such a system in the real world, we evaluate our algorithmsâ€™ performance in a real-world task of resource allocation for maternal and child care, and demonstrate near human-level reward-design performance. Our algorithm enables dynamically adjusting policies to match human-specified outcomes, using only language prompts as input.

2 Related Work

RMABs The restless multi-armed bandit problem introduced by Whittle Whittle ( 1988 ) , is classically solved through the Whittle index policy Weber and Weiss ( 1990 ); Glazebrook et al. ( 2006 ) . Subsequent works have generalized to multi-action RMABs Glazebrook et al. ( 2011 ); Killian et al. ( 2022 ) . RMABs gained prominence in public health domains and are deployed to disseminate preventative healthcare information, monitor health program adherence, and model disease spread Tambe ( 2022 ); Mate et al. ( 2022 ) . However, existing works focus on fixed reward functions and fail to consider that public health planners often have evolving priorities Organization and others ( 2015 ) .

Reward Design : Designing reward functions that effectively condense long-term agent goals into immediate behavioral signals is a central problem in RL Singh et al. ( 2009 ) . Manual designs are prone to task misspecification and overfitting Booth et al. ( 2023 ) . Ho and Ermon Ho and Ermon ( 2016 ) and Hussein et al. , Hussein et al. ( 2017 ) reshape reward through expert behavior observation, but they ignored that expert examples may not be available in resource and data-limited public health domains. Using LLMs as dense reward signals have been investigated Kwon et al. ( 2022 ); Du et al. ( 2023 ) . Ma et al. Ma et al. ( 2024 ) use LLMs to output reward function code from language-specified goals. However, above works failed to address multi-agent settings, where a central planner could prioritize certain groups through reward design.

4 Decision-Language Model for RMABs

Below, we provide an overview of the proposed DLM reward generation technique (shown Fig. 1 ). We first describe the problem setting of reward generation, and motivate the use of LLMs for reward generation from a theoretical perspective. We then discuss the prompt provided to the LLM for initial reward candidate generation. Then, we discuss the independent simulation stage which identifies an optimal policy Ï€ R â£ âˆ— superscript ğœ‹ ğ‘… \pi^{R*} under a proposed reward R ğ‘… R , and the subsequent policy outcome comparison stage that simulates the respective policy reward outcomes. To be clear, Ï€ R â£ âˆ— superscript ğœ‹ ğ‘… \pi^{R*} references the optimal policy induced by a reward function R ğ‘… R . This does not refer to policy learned under an optimal reward R âˆ— superscript ğ‘… R^{*} . Finally, we discuss the LLM reflection stage which performs policy outcome comparison and identifies successful candidates to guide future in-context learning for LLM reward generation.

4.2 Sample Inefficiency of Fitness Function

In order to evaluate each task description that we provide, we manually define a â€˜ground truth fitness functionâ€™. This is the reward function against which the learned policies are evaluated. However, this fitness function is unknown to the LLM. The â€˜baseâ€™ policy in our comparison is obtained by training an RL policy to maximize the discounted cumulative reward obtained by this ground truth fitness function and serves as a baseline to our experiments. We want to note that, despite being the â€˜true reward functionâ€™, this might not be the best reward function to learn the optimal policy in a learning theoretic sense. This is usually the case when rewards are sparse (i.e, hard to obtain) from simple policies and the sparsity of the reward signal makes learning hard. Thus, reward shaping/ reward engineering has been extensively studied in the literature ( Dann et al. ( 2023 ); Sutton and Barto ( 2018 ); Ng et al. ( 1999 ); Singh et al. ( 2010 ) ). The idea here is to use domain knowledge and design a different, dense reward whose optimal policy is the same as that of the original reward. However, the learning algorithm deployed finds it much easier to learn the optimal policy via the shaped reward. While the existing works (eg Ng et al. ( 1999 ) ) show that reward shaping methods can provably help learning in the single agent setting, their results apply to the multi-agent problem of RMABs, where the Lagrangian relaxation decouples the value function across arms and allows us to focus on separate single-agent MDPs. In this work, we eschew the careful human design of the reward function, and allow an LLM to assume this role. Our thesis is that the world knowledge the LLM obtains during its training, along with reflection, equips it with the domain knowledge essential to design efficient reward functions. Automated design of such reward functions have been explored in the literature: Mataric ( 1994 ); Sorg et al. ( 2010 ); Zheng et al. ( 2020 ) . Here, a meta-network is trained to learn the best rewards along with the policy network which is trained to learn the optimal policy for a given reward. In our work, reflection serves a similar purpose as training of the meta-network but with the number of steps being dramatically smaller and the output being in the form of code, making it interpretable.

4.3 Provided DLM Context

In the reward candidate generation phase, we prompt the LLM with three key contextual components (shown Alg. 1 , line 5). First, we provide a human-written language command that elucidates desired policy outcome. In practice, this is the only human input required for the proposed DLM technique.

Second, we provide arm feature category information, denoted ğ³ ğ³ \mathbf{z} . In the public health setting, features may include demographic information, socioeconomic data, or othe descriptors relevant to policy outcomes. We propose that LLMs may reasonably interpret the contextual relevance of respective features from a given language prompt, and adeptly propose reward functions using critical feature information to converge efficiently on desired policy outcomes. That is, given a language prompt â„“ â„“ \ell we consider that LLMs may be used to extract the directly relevant features ğ³ d â€‹ i â€‹ r âŠ† ğ³ subscript ğ³ ğ‘‘ ğ‘– ğ‘Ÿ ğ³ \mathbf{z}_{dir}\subseteq\mathbf{z} explicitly referenced in â„“ â„“ \ell to design a reward function R ğ‘… R .

Third, we provide context regarding the RMAB problem formulation and corresponding code implementation. Specifically, we include information describing the state variable as a per-arm binary value, as well as syntax for accessing feature information from the codebase. From this context, we evaluate the ability for the LLM to propose reward functions in the form of code, as previously proposed by Ma et al. ( 2024 ); Li et al. ( 2023 ) .

4.4 DRL Simulation

4.5 Reflection Stage

We propose the reflection comparison stage to enable LLM self-reflection and iteration on proposed rewards. The outcome comparison produces language output showing, under each proposed reward R i subscript ğ‘… ğ‘– R_{i} , the final simulated distribution of states across key feature groups. Distributions, for instance, may be shown over age, gender, income, or other pre-defined feature groupings. This comparison is used in place of a numerical, scalar feedback function. Prior works Ma et al. ( 2024 ) assume access to some base fitness functions for self-reflection ( F ğ¹ F as defined above) Singh et al. ( 2009 ) and also do not consider the multi-agent setting. In the resource-constrained public health domain, we do not assume we have access to this ground truth function. Thus, rather than providing feedback from the base fitness function, we instead show state-feature distributions, or the states achieved across feature groups g âˆˆ ğ† ğ‘” ğ† g\in\mathbf{G} ; for example, over age or income brackets. Intuitively, because we focus on resource allocation in the public health domain, we propose that simulated state-feature distributions provide sufficient signal for the LLM to analyze the efficacy of proposed rewards , and select top candidate examples for future in-context learning.

We provide an overview of the policy outcome comparison procedure in Alg. 2 . Given trained policy and critic network Î¸ , Ï• ğœƒ italic-Ï• \theta,\phi , final lambda value Î» ğœ† \lambda , and feature matrix ğ™ âˆˆ â„ N Ã— m ğ™ superscript â„ ğ‘ ğ‘š \mathbf{Z}\in\mathbb{R}^{N\times m} , we first simulate over n s subscript ğ‘› s n_{\text{s}} evaluation timesteps (Alg. 2 lines 7:11). Note that we store only accumulated agent states ğ’ ğ’ \mathbf{S} ; we use accumulated per-agent states to later reflect on achieved allocation outcomes. We then compute the percentage of reward attributed to arms within each sub-group g âˆˆ ğ† ğ‘” ğ† g\in\mathbf{G} (Alg. 2 lines 13:16). Finally, we report final state-feature distributions in an output string. We then query an LLM to select the best candidate example given the original prompt â„“ â„“ \ell and the outcome distribution string ğ’´ ğ’´ \mathcal{Y} (Alg. 1 lines 22:24). This selected example is then added as context in the prompt of the next iteration of reward generation (Alg. 1 line 25).

This approach has two key strengths. First, we enable greater transparency of our approach, by using state-feature distributions to evaluate the effectiveness of a policy under a specified reward Ï€ R â£ âˆ— superscript ğœ‹ ğ‘… \pi^{R*} . By providing only simulated outcome distributions to the reflection LLM, we ensure that self-reflection focuses only on alignment between the stated language goal and the resource allocation outcomes of our public health settings, without assuming any access to ground truth reward . Second, we allow for greater flexibility; by investigating only the outcome distributions of the proposed rewards, rather than original policies themselves, we enable a model-agnostic approach to self-iteration in reward design.

5 Experimental Evaluation

We evaluate DLM in a simulated setting representative of real-world resource allocation for maternal healthcare. We collaborate with ARMMAN, a non-profit based in India that enrolls pregnant women into a voice messaging service sharing preventative care information. We use real-world data from a service quality improvement study of 44,000 mothers collected by ARMMAN in January 2022 to construct the environmentâ€™s transition probabilities. This program, specifically focused on low-income communities Killian et al. ( 2022 ) , employs health workers to provide service calls to high-risk beneficiaries; however, the number of women enrolled in the program far outnumbers the number of health workers. As such, the aim is to identify beneficiaries to call to maximize engagement with the program, allowing for the most efficient allocation of available resources.

5.1 Tasks, Baselines, and Metrics

We provide experimental results for 11 distinct resource allocation prompts, given in AppendixÂ E . We separate tasks into three broad difficulty levels: simple single-feature tasks, middle-complexity multiple-feature tasks, and challenging, highly ambiguous tasks requiring complete inference of relevant features (see Figure 2 ). For each prompt, we compute normalized performance over 10 seeds; we describe the normalization equation below. To evaluate our proposed Decision-Language Model (DLM), we compare against several baseline reward functions:

Random : This policy samples arms uniformly at random. Through normalization, we set the random reward function performance score to be 0, as our floor. This would be equivalent to solely maximizing for entropy, or simply a constant non-negative reward for any action. No Action : This policy samples no arms at each timestep. In most cases this will yield a negative normalized score, although in certain sparse reward tasks this may be close to the random policy. Default : This policy is trained with the same underlying algorithm as DLM, but the reward function is set to prioritize all beneficiaries equally ; thus, for each arm, reward=1 for a positive state and reward=0 for a negative state. Most prior work in RMABs assume this reward. Base : This baseline sets the reward equal to the ground truth fitness function that all other methods are evaluated against. We use this reward as the consistent standard against which we measure the performance of our proposed method and other baselines. To be clear, each method uses a different reward at train time, but uses Base reward at evaluation time. We normalize with Base so that normalized performance using Base is 1 for each task. DLM (No Reflection) : This version of our proposed method ablates the reflection and iterative refinement process. It allows us to assess the importance of the reflection loop in improving the quality of the LLM-generated reward functions. DLM (Reflection) : This is the full version of our proposed method.

Thus, we compute mean normalized reward as the average reward achieved for each policy, over 10 training seeds, using base reward during evaluation of each respective policy . We then normalize each reward R ğ‘… R as ( R âˆ’ R rand ) / ( R base âˆ’ R rand ) ğ‘… subscript ğ‘… rand subscript ğ‘… base subscript ğ‘… rand ({R-R_{\textit{rand}}})/{(R_{\textit{base}}-R_{\textit{rand}}}) . A normalized reward of 0 therefore implies a policyâ€™s performance equivalent to random allocation, while a normalized reward of 1 implies performance at the level of base reward policy. We additionally show the â€œno actionâ€ policy illustrating reward under a zero allocation strategy.

5.2 Training Details

We use the Gemini Pro LLM model Team et al. ( 2023 ) from Google to generate reward functions, and train our downstream policy with RL using PPO Schulman et al. ( 2017 ) and the generated reward function. The downstream policy is trained for 2 2 2 epochs total to simulate a few-sample regime and prevent overfitting. We do a total of 2 2 2 rounds of reflection and generate 2 2 2 candidate reward functions per round. As detailed in FigureÂ 2 , we evaluate for a total 10 10 10 seeds, each seed evaluating for 50 50 50 separate trials and 10 10 10 steps per trial, totaling 5000 5000 5000 total steps per task.

5.3 DLM Success and Failure Cases

We present the experimental evaluation of DLM in Figure 2 . We find that the proposed DLM technique is a capable reward designer across a broad range of tasks in public health. This demonstrates, to the best of our knowledge, first example of LLMs as capable policy designers for resource allocation tasks in public health. Note that we evaluate under a sample-limited regime; thus, results demonstrate the ability to converge under limited samples to an optimal policy for a given prompt. Given this setting, we make several observations on the results in Figure 2 .

Achieving base reward performance : We find DLM is able to reach the achieved base reward performance across a broad range of tasks. In particular, we find that the reflection process is able to improve the performance of the LLM in 9 out of 11 tasks, nearly reaching base reward in many circumstances. We find, in many cases, that LLMs can indeed identify the relevant features to use in proposed reward functions. An example can be seen for the task of biasing toward either tail of the age distribution ( Age Distribution Tail Emphasis ), from which the LLM is able to generate the base reward zeroshot:

â¬‡
state * ( agent_feats . youngest_agegroup or agent_feats . oldest_agegroup )

Please see AppendixÂ G for all generated reward functions.

Benefits of reflection : We observe that the proposed DLM reflection technique, which grounds LLM reward generation by incorporating feedback from RMAB simulations, is able to consistently align policies closer to the desired task. We note, however, that the degree of improvement from reflection may vary by task type. For instance, in cases with extremely simple prompts, for example single feature group preferences, reward reflection tends not to substantially enhance allocation outcomes over the zeroshot LLM-proposed rewards (i.e. Age Distribution Tail Emphasis above).

Additionally, for ambiguous prompts, such as Technologically Challenged , we find that reflection may not have sufficient guidance to meaningfully iterate on proposed rewards. Further, for cases with extreme ambiguity, requiring high degrees of reasoning, the LLM frequently responded similar to â€There was not enough information specified to solve the taskâ€ . Thus, no zeroshot reward was proposed, obviating the benefits of reflection. One potential solution may be to add a human in the proposal loop, to further specify prompts in highly ambiguous cases. We leave these potential strategies for addressing highly ambiguous tasks to future work.

Misguided LLM reward proposals : We note that in certain cases, proposed rewards may have extremely poor performance prior to reflection (i.e. task Older Bias ). In these cases, we observe that, while a task may be semantically simple, the LLM may attempt to use multiple features improperly. For example, for Older Bias , the LLM proposed:

â¬‡
state * agent_feats . secondoldest_agegroup * agent_feats . oldest_agegroup

Above, the LLM incorrectly uses features in the reward function, as an arm cannot be in both the second-oldest and the oldest age group simultaneously. Thus, in cases where improperly designed rewards are proposed, reflection is often helpful (see Appendix F ). For more examples of generated reward functions, please see AppendixÂ G .

Middle-complexity tasks : We observe that the reflection procedure is most consistently helpful for the â€œmiddle rangeâ€ of tasks that involve a composition of feature groups within the reasoning capabilities of the LLM. Many real world applications fall into this category. For example, in ARMMANâ€™s Kilkari program (a national level program in India operational across 19 states) Bashingwa et al. ( 2021 ) , different regions may have slightly different policy requirements, which a state program manager can achieve directly through language interfacing with DLM. More generally, complex goals that cannot easily be translated into updated policies by public health practitioners also fall into this category.

5.4 DLM Reflection Example

In FigureÂ 3 we visualize state-feature distributions for two candidate rewards generated by the LLM. The LLM selected best index is highlighted with a green box. We show 4 (out of 14 total) relevant feature categories: age, income, education, and phone owners. We observe that the DLM selection is often able to reasonably interpret unambiguous commands, such as prioritizing older ages, and select the distribution that best achieves the given prompt. However, we note that for more ambiguous criteria, such as â€œtechnologically challengedâ€, the DLM selection choice is oftentimes more opaque; while the base reward for this prompt considers only income and phone ownership, additional features such as education level may also be considered for selection. In these cases, additional human feedback may be required to better disambiguate prompts for improved reflection. We provide full reward reflection logs for the below examples in Appendix F .

5.5 Exceeding Base in Critical Low Income

We find that empirically for the â€œCritical Low Incomeâ€ task the LLM is actually able to improve over the base reward. We find empirically that the DLM model often proposes a reward that is of much larger scaling than the original reward. For a representative example, we show a sample reward generated by the LLM for the Critical Low Income prompt:

â¬‡
(100 * state * agent_feats . no_or_lowest_income ) + (100 * state * agent_feats . second_lowest_income ) + state

In comparison, this is the corresponding base reward:

â¬‡
state + state * 10 * if_ ( agent_feats . no_or_lowest_income or agent_feats . second_lowest_income or agent_feats . third_lowest_income )

As our results in FigureÂ 2 are evaluated in the low finite-sample regime, where there is not many gradient steps taken, sample efficiency becomes extremely important. In this case, because the reward function generated by the LLM gives an order of magnitude higher weighting to specific arms, it seems likely that the underlying policy gradient algorithm PPO gains sample efficiency in our setting. It is important to note that the improvement that the LLM yields over the base reward will shrink as the number of samples taken during training goes to infinity, as by definition the base reward defines the optimal policy. However, the highly shaped reward given by the LLM in this setting helps PPO converge faster for this task . It is also important to note that the base reward may not be the most sample efficient reward; other more complex rewards relying on correlated features or with different reward scaling will likely also gain efficiency. This also opens the possibility of achieving potential superhuman performance on our task in the future.

6 Conclusion

We propose a Decision-Language Model for resource allocation tasks in public health. The proposed model can take language prompts describing complex, potentially ambiguous policy outcome goals as input, and generate downstream control policies specialized for such goals. The proposed LLM-based approach can accurately capture the referenced prompt features and design effective reward functions in the form of code. Critically, our algorithms enable self-iteration on proposed reward functions in a fully automated fashion. By grounding LLM reward proposals with outcome distributions from RMAB simulations, we demonstrate the ability for the proposed DLM model to achieve near-human performance in public health.

Ethical Statement

Future deployment of this technology could yield large societal benefit by improving public health outcomes and enabling more targeted policies. For our experiments, consent is obtained from every beneficiary enrolling in the ARMMANâ€™s mobile health program (see also Appendix A ). However, constraining the deployed system to exhibiting only safe behavior is extremely important. One should take steps towards responsible deployment by performing human-in-the-loop verification before any learned policy allocation and implementing more traditional fallback systems not reliant on AI. We also address fairness in Appendix B .

APPENDIX:
A Decision-Language Model (DLM) for Dynamic Restless Multi-Armed Bandit Tasks in Public Health

Appendix A Data usage, consent, and secondary analysis

The data is collected from a service quality improvement study of 44K mothers conducted by ARMMAN in January 2022, and consent is obtained from every beneficiary enrolling in the NGOâ€™s mobile health program. The data collected through the program is owned by the NGO and only the NGO is allowed to share data. The data exchange and usage were regulated by clearly defined exchange protocols including anonymization, read-access only to researchers, restricted use of the data for research purposes only, and approval by ARMMANâ€™s ethics review committee. No personally identifiable information (PII) is available to authors. We use anonymized call listenership logs to calculate empirical transition probabilities in experiments. Our experiment falls into secondary analysis of the data shared by ARMMAN and does not involve the deployment of the proposed algorithm or any other baselines to the service call program.

Appendix B Addressing Fairness

When LLM used is not well-aligned or calibrated to human values, there may be issues of fairness or bias. Although this work is a secondary analysis does not involve deployment of propose algorithms, future works on field studies may imposing fairness constraints on the reward function generation and use automatic detection of unfairness Dwork et al. [ 2012 ] to incorporate fairness. For future works on deployment, to ensure safe and responsible deployment, it would be interesting to study how to detect given prompts that are designed similarly to a leading question to induce hidden biases.
